SIMPLE: fiscal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fiscal
<hw>Fis"cal</hw> <pr>(f⟦icr⟧s"k⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>fiscal</ets>, L. <ets>fiscalis</ets>, fr. <ets>fiscus</ets>. See
<er>Fisc</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining to the public treasury or
revenue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fiscal</qex> arrangements of government.</q> <rj><qau>A.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fiscal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fiscal
<hw>Fis"cal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The income of a prince
or a state; revenue; exchequer.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A treasurer.</def> <rj><au>H.
Swinburne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A public officer in Scotland who prosecutes in petty
criminal cases; -- called also <altname>procurator
fiscal</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The solicitor in Spain and Portugal; the
attorney-general.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fisetic</ent>⟦br⟧
